<subSubSection id="4169EB303E7F2D20509C9A6203181979" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" type="notes">
<paragraph id="4DCD6E4936E01A8AA916CB7513420AD1" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C8E7D9CCD93BB41B582C34BF15CF3D1E" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">
[
<emphasis id="AB7DEE3DE343BDBDAAD7DC4F952C4698" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">11 orders: 29 families: 58 genera: 78 species</emphasis>
]
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="207173F13115423416458F62D1AF450A" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">
Both 
<taxonomicName id="F62E14D1958F7ACCCB12927894A639FE" class="Actinopterygii" genus="Diplosoma" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="class">Actinopterygii</taxonomicName>
(ray-finned fish) and 
<taxonomicName id="4607ECF4356D0DF5F9B37B2503E0B9BC" class="Chondrichthyes" genus="Diplosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="class">Chondrichthyes</taxonomicName>
(cartilaginous fish) are treated below.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="492F319589304B2915F185F99758AC38" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">
' 
<taxonomicName id="AC6294E19DFAD5A38BE9DA25613FAB3D" class="Actinopterygii" genus="Diplosoma" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="class">Actinopterygii</taxonomicName>
' is formed from the Latin 'actino-', &quot;having rays&quot;, and the Ancient Greek 
<normalizedToken id="6B026E9C24AD35ADD29E53291C198945" originalValue="πτέρυξ">πτέρυξ</normalizedToken>
(
<normalizedToken id="D37BB54AE107F13A13A538104754CF87" originalValue="ptérux">pterux</normalizedToken>
), meaning 
<normalizedToken id="A41CB668EE8CC81E810F58A7591567E2" originalValue="“wings”">&quot;wings&quot;</normalizedToken>
or 
<normalizedToken id="CAD03B4162B52A09539C383F140B41A8" originalValue="“fins.”">&quot;fins.&quot;</normalizedToken>
' 
<taxonomicName id="AC2356FCCBEEFC3D48F4A99A8686A9BE" class="Chondrichthyes" genus="Diplosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="class">Chondrichthyes</taxonomicName>
' comes from the Greek 
<normalizedToken id="ED760E4A1F38F01563E13B67CA2AAE8F" originalValue="χόνδρος">xόνδρος</normalizedToken>
(
<normalizedToken id="77DDA795C830A414FCE784035013F252" originalValue="khóndros">khondros</normalizedToken>
), meaning &quot;cartilage&quot;, and 
<normalizedToken id="0F00CF07598D1C68F54BB176C83A3DDA" originalValue="ἰχθύς">ἰxθύς</normalizedToken>
(ikhthū́s), meaning &quot;fish&quot;.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="603FC1F10ECE13EFCA5D03EBD5AA1593" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">
<taxonomicName id="D5B770E20AA1DCC4509185738D0D32C1" class="Actinopterygii" genus="Diplosoma" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="class">Actinopterygii</taxonomicName>
contain over 33,000 described taxa and 
<taxonomicName id="A48E28F9E1D8EDB4ADA1472E658E7D4B" class="Chondrichthyes" genus="Diplosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="class">Chondrichthyes</taxonomicName>
(cartilaginous fish) over 1,100 taxa, including both freshwater and marine species (
<bibRefCitation id="F8A335CFE3F82039CFFC5BEC6A0800F1" author="Guinot, G." journalOrPublisher="Biological Reviews" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" pagination="950 - 981" refId="B6747870" refString="Guinot, G., Cavin, L., 2016. 'Fish' (Actinopterygii and Elasmobranchii) diversification patterns through deep time. Biological Reviews 91 (4): 950 - 981" title="' Fish' (Actinopterygii and Elasmobranchii) diversification patterns through deep time" volume="91" year="2016">Guinot and Cavin 2016</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="9906ACF0E6A6C67388090E1F8BA36001" author="Weigmann, S." journalOrPublisher="Journal of Fish Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" pagination="837 - 1037" refId="B6747879" refString="Weigmann, S., 2016. Annotated checklist of the living sharks, batoids and chimaeras (Chondrichthyes) of the world, with a focus on biogeographical diversity. Journal of Fish Biology 88 (3): 837 - 1037" title="Annotated checklist of the living sharks, batoids and chimaeras (Chondrichthyes) of the world, with a focus on biogeographical diversity" volume="88" year="2016">Weigmann 2016</bibRefCitation>
). Over 1,500 marine species are estimated to occur between the Beaufort Sea, Alaska, to the tip of Baja California, Mexico (Milton Love, pers. comm. 2020) and over 400 species reported for Canadian waters in the Northeast Pacific (
<bibRefCitation id="6A4F3C5419114BA8B2FC92FB8871FCFB" author="Paine, R. T." journalOrPublisher="American Naturalist" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6747888" refString="Peden A. E. Marine fishes of British Columbia (2002) https://ibis.geog.ubc.ca/biodiversity/efauna/documents/MarineFishofBC.pdf 2021-02-13T00:00:00+02:00" year="1966">Peden 2002</bibRefCitation>
). To date, 78 species of ray-finned fish and four species of cartilaginous fish have been reported for Galiano Island.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F945DF0D23A85A2F983FAF6CF1E527E5" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">
Marine fishes dwell in various habitats, from deep sea (pelagic) to near-shore and intertidal environments. Taxa under-represented in this dataset include 
<taxonomicName id="AADC766F73D6F2E9F5F865138402D11B" class="chondrichthyes" genus="Diplosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="class">chondrichthyes</taxonomicName>
(cartilaginous fish), myxinids (hagfish) and osmerids (smelts). These gaps reflect search efforts mostly biased toward rocky reefs and exposed beach locales, to waters &lt;30 m in depth. Agonids (poachers), pleuronectids (right-eyed flounders) and zoarcids (eelpouts) are also under-represented. These are primarily subtidal, soft substrate inhabitants, indicating that sampling has been limited in these habitats.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5EC4A821A51419A51CE3407FBA168C07" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">
Rockfish, 
<taxonomicName id="3D5CDF0DF3B7047979A161DD20DE9158" class="Mammalia" family="Sebastidae" genus="Sebastes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sebastes" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="05C4B9C062BEDA42B91CDA2A9BB16558" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Sebastes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
G. Cuvier, 1829, are a long-lived and diverse genus of fish in the Northeast Pacific, 11 of which are represented in the Galiano Island record. Species present include the threatened 
<taxonomicName id="A2497A1839BD8666E642981C5C28FB77" baseAuthorityName="Jordan &amp; Gilbert" baseAuthorityYear="1880" class="Mammalia" family="Sebastidae" genus="Sebastes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sebastes maliger" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="maliger">
<emphasis id="BAFC5D5A6668AD325310AA8D9CECAFA4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Sebastes maliger</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Jordan &amp; Gilbert, 1880) (quillback rockfish) and 
<taxonomicName id="D152C44CFB026FA21087E9F79DC60BDB" genus="S." lsidName="S. ruberrimus" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" rank="species" species="ruberrimus">
<emphasis id="43A8389A6DF5D6C0E26D2D1D98082739" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">S. ruberrimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Cramer, 1895) (yellow-eye rockfish) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="134BD2018C40F9597FE6D144DFFB8D2C" captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="F6756345" captionText="Figure 20. Sebastes ruberrimus (yelloweye rockfish) - Photograph by Don Gordon." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e76050.figure20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/564491" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">20</figureCitation>
), the latter of which is ranked as a species of special concern in Canada (
<bibRefCitation id="3B41AEF4492200A77F7AF1F90C0366FC" author="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans" journalOrPublisher="Fisheries &amp; Oceans Canada" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6756264" refString="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans, 2018. in Canada [Proposed]. Species at Risk Act Management Plan Series. Fisheries and Oceans Canada, Ottawa. iv + 32 pp." title="in Canada [Proposed]. Species at Risk Act Management Plan Series. Fisheries and Oceans Canada, Ottawa. iv + 32 pp." year="2018">Fisheries and Oceans Canada 2018b</bibRefCitation>
). This species may attain large sizes (~ 1 m, 12.6 kg). However, as with other species in the genus, it is slow to mature and reproduce and is, therefore, vulnerable to overfishing and fatality due to barotrauma from catch and release (
<bibRefCitation id="18E16D2F7F4282A332AB43242BE4B4D7" author="Rankin, P. S." journalOrPublisher="Fisheries Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" pagination="258 - 268" refId="B6756254" refString="Rankin, P. S., Hannah, R. W., Blume, M. T., Miller-Morgan, T. J., Heidel, J. R., 2017. Delayed effects of capture-induced barotrauma on physical condition and behavioral competency of recompressed yelloweye rockfish, Sebastes ruberrimus. Fisheries Research 186: 258 - 268" title="Delayed effects of capture-induced barotrauma on physical condition and behavioral competency of recompressed yelloweye rockfish, Sebastes ruberrimus" volume="186" year="2017">Rankin et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
). As a consequence, many species of 
<taxonomicName id="C15BE61405A2E356382B2240F4AAC8BD" class="Mammalia" family="Sebastidae" genus="Sebastes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Sebastes" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83C0B316FC41D9868A26FA3619617B33" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Sebastes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are at low levels of abundance in the region (
<bibRefCitation id="CFFBEEDF5FC732DAC80CB0A2C608485F" author="Canada, Fisheries and Oceans" journalOrPublisher="Fisheries &amp; Oceans Canada" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6756272" refString="Canada Fisheries and Oceans Rockfish conservation areas https://www.pac.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/fm-gp/maps-cartes/rca-acs/index-eng.html 2021-02-18T00:00:00+02:00" year="2018">Fisheries and Oceans Canada 2021</bibRefCitation>
). Spatially-managed rockfish conservation areas that remain permanently closed to all fishing and extraction activities are vital to ensure their recovery (
<bibRefCitation id="E1EBCF67E3E393349D31C304A9473231" author="Rankin, P. S." journalOrPublisher="Fisheries Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" pagination="258 - 268" refId="B6756254" refString="Rankin, P. S., Hannah, R. W., Blume, M. T., Miller-Morgan, T. J., Heidel, J. R., 2017. Delayed effects of capture-induced barotrauma on physical condition and behavioral competency of recompressed yelloweye rockfish, Sebastes ruberrimus. Fisheries Research 186: 258 - 268" title="Delayed effects of capture-induced barotrauma on physical condition and behavioral competency of recompressed yelloweye rockfish, Sebastes ruberrimus" volume="186" year="2017">Rankin et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6673D7A1EB83E80E4C7FAB73142ED0D0" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">
<taxonomicName id="EE134CB8F4E536A525A0292DF7C00A41" baseAuthorityName="Girard" baseAuthorityYear="1855" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Squalidae" genus="Squalus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Squalus suckleyi" order="Squaliformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="suckleyi">
<emphasis id="EA3087CF750AD3F6027651AFB0BCB71F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Squalus suckleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Girard, 1854 (North Pacific spiny dogfish), reported for Galiano Island, is a species of special concern in Canada (
<bibRefCitation id="E40E785E4F3A7595EF904FE983F85712" author="COSEWIC," journalOrPublisher="Committee on the Status of Endangered Wildlife in Canada" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B7630577" refString="COSEWIC, , 2011. COSEWIC assessment and status report on the North Pacific Spiny Dogfish Squalus suckleyi in Canada. Committee on the Status of Endangered Wildlife in Canada" title="COSEWIC assessment and status report on the North Pacific Spiny Dogfish Squalus suckleyi in Canada" year="2011">COSEWIC 2011</bibRefCitation>
). The near-threatened 
<taxonomicName id="E50FD4092F3313E8880C211A694C2B89" baseAuthorityName="Bonnaterre" baseAuthorityYear="1788" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Hexanchidae" genus="Hexanchus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hexanchus griseus" order="Hexanchiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="griseus">
<emphasis id="3FB5E82BD2D9FA34BAF04154EAB6BA56" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Hexanchus griseus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Bonnaterre, 1788) (bluntnose sixgill shark), is also known from adjacent waters around Mayne Island, BC. This species likely occurs around Galiano Island, though it is not reported in this dataset. One unusual report for Galiano Island is 
<taxonomicName id="79B29F22167B02F3204410300D01E8BC" authorityName="Kner" authorityYear="1859" class="Actinopterygii" family="Trachipteridae" genus="Trachipterus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trachipterus altivelis" order="Lampriformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="altivelis">
<emphasis id="4BDAC307B3E0D35710EDF433DDC3198C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Trachipterus altivelis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Kner, 1859 (king-of-the-salmon), an outer coastal species likely represented by a specimen carried in from offshore waters. Introduced fishes, such as 
<taxonomicName id="76EC8FDC3B94F2443D70A5639F069387" baseAuthorityName="Wilson" baseAuthorityYear="1811" class="Actinopterygii" family="Clupeidae" genus="Alosa" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Alosa sapidissima" order="Clupeiformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sapidissima">
<emphasis id="0D8E48DB42F16EA9343F60F3A14EB835" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Alosa sapidissima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(A. Wilson, 1811) (American shad), 
<taxonomicName id="F319DAE9F8C072BE2F4D3792C0BC8D36" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" class="Mammalia" family="Salmonidae" genus="Salmo" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Salmo salar" order="Cetacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="salar">
<emphasis id="CA9E7155CB77BDC60C8A714C48A4555D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Salmo salar</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Linnaeus, 1758 (Atlantic salmon) and 
<taxonomicName id="6B72D443ED680C6791FD7AF4C5A283DB" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" class="Mammalia" family="Salmonidae" genus="Salmo" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Salmo trutta" order="Cetacea" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="trutta">
<emphasis id="8740BBA84E0CE67C20BCE906904E4F18" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050">Salmo trutta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Linnaeus, 1758 (brown trout), are documented from waters not far from Galiano Island, though they have not yet been reported locally. References for the fishes of the Pacific coast of North America include 
<bibRefCitation id="96BC82EB7A32B2FC48545E7F7972A3D8" author="Clemens, W. A." journalOrPublisher="Fisheries Research Board of Canada, Ottawa" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6748121" refString="Clemens, W. A., Wilby, G. V., 1961. Fishes of the Pacific coast of Canada. Bulletin No. 68. Fisheries Research Board of Canada, Ottawa" title="Fishes of the Pacific coast of Canada. Bulletin No. 68" year="1961">Clemens and Wilby (1961)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="FFF6ADC9B514C2E11E8E47DD9FF08BE1" author="Hart, J. L." journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Fisheries Research Board of Canada, Ottawa" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6748137" refString="Hart, J. L., 1973. Pacific fishes of Canada. Bulletin of the Fisheries Research Board of Canada, Ottawa" title="Pacific fishes of Canada" year="1973">Hart (1973)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="1FA7206792356211562ED13B14EF348F" author="Paine, R. T." journalOrPublisher="American Naturalist" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6747888" refString="Peden A. E. Marine fishes of British Columbia (2002) https://ibis.geog.ubc.ca/biodiversity/efauna/documents/MarineFishofBC.pdf 2021-02-13T00:00:00+02:00" year="1966">Peden (2002)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="797BD923532E2094F479B1A08D4CC28F" author="Lamb, A." journalOrPublisher="Harbour Publishing, Maideira Park" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6662869" refString="Lamb, A., Hanby, B. P., 2005. Marine life of the Pacific Northwest: a photographic encyclopedia of invertebrates, seaweeds and selected fishes. Harbour Publishing, Maideira Park" title="Marine life of the Pacific Northwest: a photographic encyclopedia of invertebrates, seaweeds and selected fishes" year="2005">Lamb and Hanby (2005)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="C9182B7D0D0D030EC9AE9C289A2904BC" author="Love, M. S." journalOrPublisher="Seattle, Washington: U. S. Department of the Interior, U. S. Geological Survey, Biological Resources Division" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6747939" refString="Love, M. S., Mecklenburg, C. W., Mecklenburg, T. A., Thorsteinson, L. K., 2005. Resource inventory of marine and estuarine fishes of the west coast and Alaska: a checklist of North American Pacific and Arctic Ocean species from Baja California to the Alaska-Yukon border. Seattle, Washington: U.S. Department of the Interior, U.S. Geological Survey, Biological Resources Division" title="Resource inventory of marine and estuarine fishes of the west coast and Alaska: a checklist of North American Pacific and Arctic Ocean species from Baja California to the Alaska-Yukon border." year="2005">Love et al. (2005)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EC522EDEA363BAD68885EA80222F6A9E" author="De Maddalena, A." journalOrPublisher="Harbour Publishing, Madeira Park" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6747947" refString="De Maddalena, A., Preti, A., Polansky, T., 2007. Sharks of the Pacific Northwest, including Oregon, Washington, British Columbia &amp; Alaska. Harbour Publishing, Madeira Park" title="Sharks of the Pacific Northwest, including Oregon, Washington, British Columbia &amp; Alaska" year="2007">De Maddalena et al. (2007)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="90F099DAEABD83A7F0ED0E8F722869D8" author="Lamb, A." journalOrPublisher="Harbour Publishing, Madeira Park" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6747955" refString="Lamb, A., Edgell, P., 2010. Coastal fishes of the Pacific northwest. Revised and expanded second edition. Harbour Publishing, Madeira Park" title="Coastal fishes of the Pacific northwest. Revised and expanded second edition." year="2010">Lamb and Edgell (2010)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="733E20DFBCB4DD9543E02E4ED8CB0244" author="Harbo, R. M." journalOrPublisher="Harbour Publishing, Maideira Park" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6662898" refString="Harbo, R. M., 2011. Whelks to whales. Harbour Publishing, Maideira Park" title="Whelks to whales" year="2011">Harbo (2011)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="B5C2A966151EBE3F654FEB0CA2D878E2" author="Love, M. S." journalOrPublisher="Really Big Press, Santa Barbara" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6747963" refString="Love, M. S., 2011. Certainly more than you want to know about the fishes of the Pacific Coast. Really Big Press, Santa Barbara" title="Certainly more than you want to know about the fishes of the Pacific Coast" year="2011">Love (2011)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="BDCDE5140509806BE8687BAE15D491E4" author="Butler, J. L." journalOrPublisher="University of California Press, Berkeley" pageId="0" pageNumber="76050" refId="B6747971" refString="Butler, J. L., Love, M. S., Laidig, T. E., 2012. A guide to rockfishes, thornyheads and scorpionfishes of the Northeast Pacific. University of California Press, Berkeley" title="A guide to rockfishes, thornyheads and scorpionfishes of the Northeast Pacific" year="2012">Butler et al. (2012)</bibRefCitation>
. For annotated records of ray-finned fishes reported for Galiano Island, see supplementary materials (Suppl. material 18).
